{"title_page": "Gorkhaland Territorial Administration", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for keywords-->\n| name                            = Gorkhaland\n| native_name                     = \n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = Gorkhaland Territorial Administration\n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Autonomous regions of India|Autonomous area]]\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| image_seal                      = Gorkhaland Territorial Administration seal.png\n| seal_alt                        = Official seal\n| pushpin_map                     = India West Bengal#India\n| pushpin_label                   = Darjeeling\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location of GTA in West Bengal, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|27.03|N|88.16|E|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- location -->| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_name1               = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_type2               = District\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Darjeeling District|Darjeeling]], [[Kalimpong District|Kalimpong]]\n| established_title               = Established\n| established_date                = 14 March 2012\n| founder                         = \n| seat_type                       = [[Headquarters]]\n| seat                            = [[Darjeeling]]\n| parts_type                      = Covering Territory\n| parts_style                     = para\n| parts                           = <!--text or header for parts list-->\n| p1                              = [[Darjeeling Sadar subdivision]]\n| p2                              = [[Kurseong subdivision]]\n| p3                              = [[Mirik subdivision]]\n| p4                              = [[Siliguri subdivision]] (some part only)\n| p5                              = [[Kalimpong district]]\n<!-- government type, leaders -->| government_footnotes            = \n| leader_title1                   = \n| leader_name1                    = \n| leader_title2                   = [[Chairman]]\n| leader_name2                    = [[Anit Thapa]]\n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = 3303.98\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = 878,002\n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Nepali language|Nepali]] and [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| registration_plate              = \n| website                         = [http://gta-darjeeling.org gta-darjeeling.org]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n[[File:NE Autonomous divisions of India.svg|350px|right|North Eastern autonomous divisions]]\n\n'''Gorkhaland''' is a region in the north of the [[India]]n state of [[West Bengal]] that is administered by the '''Gorkhaland Territorial Administration''', an [[Autonomous District Council]] for the [[Darjeeling district|Darjeeling]] and [[Kalimpong district|Kalimpong]] areas.The GTA was formed in 2012 to replace the [[Darjeeling Gorkha Hill Council]], which was formed in 1988  and administered the Darjeeling hills for 23 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=728097|title=Gorkhaland Territorial Administration Agreement signed|publisher=Outlook|date=18 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603154514/http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=728097|archivedate=3 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> GTA presently has three hill subdivisions [[Darjeeling Sadar subdivision|Darjeeling]], [[Kurseong subdivision|Kurseong]] and [[Mirik subdivision|Mirik]] and some areas of [[Siliguri subdivision]] of [[Darjeeling district]] and the whole of [[Kalimpong district]] under its authority.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article2246756.ece|title=Pact signed for Gorkhaland Territorial Administration|work=The Hindu|date=18 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012|location=Chennai, India|first=Ananya|last=Dutta}}</ref>The GTA former president is Anit Thapa a resident of kurseong while the former president was Bimal gurung followed by Binay Tamang\n\n== History ==\n{{main|Gorkhaland movement}}\nGorkhaland is the name of the proposed state in India that the [[Nepali language|Nepali]]-speaking [[Indian Gorkha|Gorkha]] ethnic group in [[Darjeeling district|Darjeeling]] [[Kalimpong]] and the [[Dooars]] in north of [[West Bengal]] have expressed a desire to create.A demand for a separate administrative unit in Darjeeling has existed since 1909, when the Hillmen's Association of Darjeeling submitted a memorandum to [[Minto-Morley Reforms]] demanding a separate administrative setup. The term ''Gorkhaland'' was coined by [[Subhash Ghisingh]], leader of [[Gorkha National Liberation Front]], who led a violent agitation for its formation in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darjeelingtimes.com/news/Interviews/Interview-with-subash-ghisingh.html|title=Interview with Subhash Ghisingh|work=Darjeeling Times|date=11 January 2008|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> This movement culminated with the formation of Darjeeling Gorkha Hill Council (DGHC) in 1988. The DGHC did not fulfill its goal of forming a new state, which led to the downfall of Subhash Ghisingh<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/03/11/stories/2008031154731100.htm|title=Subhas Ghising resigns|work=The Hindu|date=11 March 2008|accessdate=16 March 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> and the rise of another party [[Gorkha Janmukti Morcha]] (GJM) headed by [[Bimal Gurung]] in 2007, which launched a second agitation for a Gorkhaland state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.rediff.com/column/2010/jun/03/gjm-leader-bimal-gurung-utterly-self-possessed-and-apparently-ruthless.htm|title=GJM leader Bimal Gurung|work=The Hindu|date=3 June 2010|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Formation of GTA ===\nAfter three years of agitation for a state of Gorkhaland led by GJM, the GJM reached an agreement with the state government to form a semi-autonomous body to administer the Darjeeling hills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/nation/article432036.ece|title=Darjeeling issue solved: Mamata|publisher=Express Buzz|date=8 June 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> A bill for the creation of GTA was passed in the [[West Bengal Legislative Assembly]] on 2 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-03/kolkata/30110031_1_territorial-administration-bill-harka-bahadur-chhetri-gjm|title=GTA Bill passed with 54 amendments|work=The Times of India|date=3 September 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> The GTA aimed to have administrative, executive and financial powers but no legislative powers. A 10-member joint verification committee headed by a retired High Court judge examined the demand to bring the Gorkha-inhabited pockets of the Dooars and the [[Terai]] under the GTA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110730/jsp/frontpage/story_14309540.jsp|title=Ex-judge to head hill committee|work=The Telegraph|date=30 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012|location=Calcutta, India}}</ref>\n\n=== Memorandum of Agreement ===\nThe Memorandum of Agreement<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darjeelingtimes.com/images/stories/news_images/2011/jul11/jul15/finalmos.pdf|title=Full text of GTA MoA|work=Darjeeling Times|date=15 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> for GTA was signed on 18 July 2011 at Pintail Village near [[Siliguri]] in the presence of Union Home Minister [[P. Chidambaram]], West Bengal chief minister [[Mamata Banerjee]] and Gorkha Janmukti Morcha leaders.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.indiangorkhas.in/2011/07/gorkhaland-territorial-administration.html|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305003752/http://www.indiangorkhas.in/2011/07/gorkhaland-territorial-administration.html|url-status = dead|archive-date = 2016-03-05|title = Gorkhaland Territorial Administration (GTA)|work = Indian Gorkhas}}</ref> The agreement was signed by West Bengal Home Secretary G.D. Gautama, Union Home Ministry Joint Secretary K.K. Pathak and GJM general secretary Roshan Giri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.outlookindia.com/item.aspx?728097|title=Gorkhaland Territorial Administration Agreement signed|publisher=Outlook|date=18 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719180442/http://news.outlookindia.com/item.aspx?728097|archivedate=19 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Demand for GATA ===\nOn 29 October 2011, the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha and the Akhil Bharatiya Adivasi Vikas Parishad (ABAVP), Dooars Unit signed an 18-point agreement at Mongpoo, after which these organizations jointly proposed a new administrative body called the Gorkhaland and Adivasi Territorial Administration (GATA) in place of the GTA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/delhi/plea-to-rename-gorkha-council_738966.html|title=Plea to rename Gorkha council|publisher=Zee News|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> The ABAVP decided to agree to incorporate 196 mouzas of the Dooars and 199 mouzas of the Terai region into the proposed GATA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thestatesman.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=388679&catid=72|title=GJMM-ABAVP joint deputation on GATA|publisher=The Statesman|date=2 November 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== President's assent and high-power committee report ===\nThe [[President of India]] [[Pratibha Patil]] gave her assent to the GTA Bill of West Bengal on 7 March 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/Chunk-HT-UI-IndiaSectionPage-TopStories/President-gives-her-assent-to-the-GTA-Bill/Article1-822330.aspx|title=President gives her assent to the GTA Bill|work=Hindustan Times|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\nThe West Bengal government issued a gazette notification for the GTA Act on 14 March 2012, signalling preparations for elections for the GTA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-15/kolkata/31196654_1_darjeeling-hills-gorkha-janmukti-morcha-gjm|title=Gorkha territory readies for polls|work=The Times of India|date=15 March 2012|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> In a meeting held on 24 March 2012 between GJM leaders and the West Bengal government, it was decided that the election to the GTA would be held in the end of June or in July 2012.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/WestBengal/High-powered-committee-on-GTA-emerges-as-a-perfect-instrument-to-resolve-impasse/Article1-830368.aspx|title=High-powered committee on GTA emerges as a perfect instrument to resolve impasse|work=Hindustan Times|date=24 March 2012|accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref> The Justice Sen Committee would be requested to submit its report on the inclusion of additional areas of Terai and Dooars in the GTA by early June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=757073|title=GJM climbs down GTA demand, says polls in June\u2013July|publisher=Outlook|date=24 March 2012|accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref> The WB government released a list of 45 constituencies of the GTA on 26 May 2012 to which elections are to be held in July 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Gorkhaland-Territorial-Administration-draft-lists-17-new-constituencies/articleshow/13548203.cms|title=Gorkhaland Territorial Administration draft lists 17 new constituencies|work=The Times of India|date=27 May 2012|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> The high-powered committee headed by retired judge [[Shyamal Kumar Sen]] that was set up by the West Bengal government recommended inclusion of just five [[mouza]]s under the proposed GTA although the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha had demanded 398 mouzas from the Dooars and Terai regions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/darjeeling-might-be-violent-again/articleshow/13966042.cms|title=Darjeeling might be violent again|work=The Economic Times|date=9 June 2012|accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref> The West Bengal government announced that it would set up a three-member \"Fact Verification Committee\" to go into the recommendations of Justice Sen Committee after the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha rejected its report.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/generalnews/news/govt-to-setfact-verification-committeegjm-demand/21365/|title=Govt to set up Fact Verification committee on GJM demand|work=Business Standard|date=16 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> The [[Calcutta High Court]] admitted on 19 June 2012 the case moved by Gorkha National Liberation Front leader Subhash Ghisingh challenging the legality of the GTA. Justice Dipankar Dutta told the three signatories to the GTA agreement \u2013 the central government, the state government and the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha \u2013 to file affidavits stating their stand on Ghisingh's contention.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120620/jsp/siliguri/story_15631990.jsp#.T-H8sbWES8o|title=HC allows Ghisingh GTA plea \u2013 Affidavit order for govts & Morcha|work=The Telegraph|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=20 June 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Our|last=Legal}}</ref>\n\n== GTA election 2012 ==\nThe West Bengal government announced that the election for the GTA would be held on 29 July 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-26/kolkata/32424010_1_gorkha-janmukti-morcha-gjm-shyamal-sen-committee-report|title=State sets July 29 date for GTA polls|work=The Times of India|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> The Gorkha Janmukti Morcha announced that it would contest the GTA polls, which it had earlier threatened to boycott over the Justice Sen-headed committee recommendations on territorial inclusion of the Dooars and Terai that it had rejected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/WestBengal/Gorkha-Janmukti-Morcha-to-contest-GTA-elections/Article1-881430.aspx|title=Gorkha Janmukti Morcha to contest GTA elections|work=The Hindustan Times|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701015423/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/WestBengal/Gorkha-Janmukti-Morcha-to-contest-GTA-elections/Article1-881430.aspx|archivedate=1 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After a period of silence, the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha announced the names of its GTA election nominees.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120706/jsp/siliguri/story_15697611.jsp|title=GTA list of 32 but no Gurung|work=The Telegraph|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Vivek|last=Chhetri}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120707/jsp/frontpage/story_15700400.jsp|title=Gurung in GTA fray|work=The Telegraph|date=6 July 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Vivek|last=Chhetri}}</ref> Parties that formed the Gorkhaland Task Force ([[Communist Party of Revolutionary Marxists|CPRM]], [[ABGL]], [[Bharatiya Gorkha Parisangh]], [[Gorkha National Liberation Front (C.K. Pradhan)|GNLF(C)]], Gorkhaland Rajya Nirman Morcha and others) decided not contest the GTA elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.news.yahoo.com/gjm-faces-heat-rival-parties-strong-arm-tactics-144738644.html|title=GJM faces heat from rival parties for strong-arm tactics|publisher=Yahoo News|date=7 July 2012|accessdate=8 July 2012}}</ref> Both [[CPI(M)]] and [[Trinamool Congress]] fielded candidates in the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/darjeeling-gta-election-is-taking-one-sided-shape/articleshow/14717481.cms|title=Darjeeling GTA election is taking one sided shape|work=The Economic Times|date=6 July 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> The GNLF decided to boycott the elections and its chairman filed a case in the Kolkata High Court challenging the GTA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/article3583517.ece|title=Gurung challenges Ghising to contest GTA polls|work=The Hindu|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012|location=Chennai, India|first=Marcus|last=Dam}}</ref> The CPI(M) withdrew the nominations of all its 13 candidates from the GTA elections, alleging threats and intimidation by the GJM<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstrackindia.com/newsdetails/2012/07/12/254--All-CPI-M-candidates-pull-out-of-Gorkhaland-polls-.html|title=All CPI-M candidates pull out of Gorkhaland polls|publisher=News track India/IANS|date=12 July 2012|accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref> and the GJM received 28 seats of the GTA uncontested.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120713/jsp/siliguri/story_15722547.jsp|title=Morcha gets 28, Gurung thanks CPM|work=The Telegraph|date=13 July 2012|accessdate=15 July 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first1=Vivek|last1=Chhetri|first2=Avijit|last2=Sinha}}</ref> In the elections of the remaining 17 seats of the GTA held on 29 July 2012, GJM candidates won from all the constituencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darjeelingtimes.com/main-news/politics/4936-gjm-sweeps-maiden-gta-polls-not-to-give-up-gorkhaland-demand.html|title=GJM sweeps maiden GTA polls, not to give up Gorkhaland demand|publisher=Darjeeling Times/IANS|date=2 August 2012|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> Sanchabir Subba, the rebel GJM candidate from Gitdabling-Nimbong, narrowly lost to the party's official contestant Kalyan Dewan by 677 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120803/jsp/siliguri/story_15806782.jsp#.UB4clk0gfao|title=Lone rebel Subba loses|work=The Telegraph|date=3 August 2012|accessdate=5 August 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Rajeev|last=Ravidas}}</ref> The newly elected members of the GTA were sworn in on 4 August 2012 at Darjeeling in the presence of home minister [[Sushil Kumar Shinde]] and West Bengal chief minister Mamata Banerjee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Gorkha-Territorial-Administration-members-sworn-in-Shinde-Mamata-assure-support/articleshow/15352094.cms |title=Gorkha Territorial Administration members sworn in; Shinde, Mamata assure support |work=The Times of India |date=5 August 2012 |accessdate=5 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804212156/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Gorkha-Territorial-Administration-members-sworn-in-Shinde-Mamata-assure-support/articleshow/15352094.cms |archivedate=4 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n{{electiontable|Gorkhaland Territorial Administration election, 2012 |Summary of results of the Gorkhaland Territorial Administration election, 2012|sortable=yes}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://darjeeling.gov.in/GTAelected_candidates.html|title=GTA Elections 2012|work=Darjeeling.gov.in|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n|-\n|<!-- color -->\n|Political Party\n|Seats Contested\n|Seats Won\n|Net Change in Seats\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Gorkha Janmukti Morcha}}\n||45||45||-|-\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|All India Trinamool Congress}}\n||17||0||-|-\n|-\n|}\n\n== Regional Political Parties of Gorkhaland ==\n* [[Gorkha Janmukti Morcha]] (GJM)\n* [[Gorkha National Liberation Front]] (GNLF)\n* [[Gorkha National Liberation Front (C.K. Pradhan)]] (GNLF-P)\n* [[Gorkha Rashtriya Congress]]\n* [[Akhil Bharatiya Gorkha League]] / All India Gorkha League (ABGL)\n* [[Bharatiya Gorkha Janashakti]]\n* [[Bharatiya Gorkha Parisangh]] \n* [[Communist Party of Revolutionary Marxists]] (CPRM)\n* [[Sikkim Rashtriya Mukti Morcha]] (SRMM)\n* [[Gorkhaland Rajya Nirman Morcha]] (GRNM)\n* [[Darjeeling Sikkim Merger Forum]] (DSMF)\n* [[Bharatiya Nepali Bir Gorkha]] (BNBG)\n* [[Matri Bhumi Surakhsa Sangathan]] (MBSS)\n* [[Jan Andolan Party]] (JAP)\n* [[Tarai Gorkha Ekta Sangh]] (TGES)\n=== Defunct Political Parties of Gorkhaland ===\n* [[Sikkim Janashakti Party ]] (SJP) {merged with [[Indian National Congress]] in 1999}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Autonomous regions of India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Autonomous administrative divisions of India}}\n\n[[Category:Politics of Gorkhaland]]\n[[Category:Government of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Autonomous regions of India]]\n[[Category:2011 in Indian politics]]\n[[Category:Politics of Darjeeling district]]\n[[Category:Darjeeling district]]\n[[Category:Kalimpong district]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for keywords-->\n| name                            = Gorkhaland\n| native_name                     = \n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = Gorkhaland Territorial Administration\n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Autonomous regions of India|Autonomous area]]\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| image_seal                      = Gorkhaland Territorial Administration seal.png\n| seal_alt                        = Official seal\n| pushpin_map                     = India West Bengal#India\n| pushpin_label                   = Darjeeling\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location of GTA in West Bengal, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|27.03|N|88.16|E|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- location -->| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_name1               = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_type2               = District\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Darjeeling District|Darjeeling]], [[Kalimpong District|Kalimpong]]\n| established_title               = Established\n| established_date                = 14 March 2012\n| founder                         = \n| seat_type                       = [[Headquarters]]\n| seat                            = [[Darjeeling]]\n| parts_type                      = Covering Territory\n| parts_style                     = para\n| parts                           = <!--text or header for parts list-->\n| p1                              = [[Darjeeling Sadar subdivision]]\n| p2                              = [[Kurseong subdivision]]\n| p3                              = [[Mirik subdivision]]\n| p4                              = [[Siliguri subdivision]] (some part only)\n| p5                              = [[Kalimpong district]]\n<!-- government type, leaders -->| government_footnotes            = \n| leader_title1                   = \n| leader_name1                    = \n| leader_title2                   = [[Chairman]]\n| leader_name2                    = [[Anit Thapa]]\n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = 3303.98\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = 878,002\n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Nepali language|Nepali]] and [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| registration_plate              = \n| website                         = [http://gta-darjeeling.org gta-darjeeling.org]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n[[File:NE Autonomous divisions of India.svg|350px|right|North Eastern autonomous divisions]]\n\n'''Gorkhaland''' is a region in the north of the [[India]]n state of [[West Bengal]] that is administered by the '''Gorkhaland Territorial Administration''', an [[Autonomous District Council]] for the [[Darjeeling district|Darjeeling]] and [[Kalimpong district|Kalimpong]] areas.The GTA was formed in 2012 to replace the [[Darjeeling Gorkha Hill Council]], which was formed in 1988  and administered the Darjeeling hills for 23 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=728097|title=Gorkhaland Territorial Administration Agreement signed|publisher=Outlook|date=18 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603154514/http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=728097|archivedate=3 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> GTA presently has three hill subdivisions [[Darjeeling Sadar subdivision|Darjeeling]], [[Kurseong subdivision|Kurseong]] and [[Mirik subdivision|Mirik]] and some areas of [[Siliguri subdivision]] of [[Darjeeling district]] and the whole of [[Kalimpong district]] under its authority.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article2246756.ece|title=Pact signed for Gorkhaland Territorial Administration|work=The Hindu|date=18 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012|location=Chennai, India|first=Ananya|last=Dutta}}</ref>The GTA present president is Anit Thapa a resident of kurseong.\n\n== History ==\n{{main|Gorkhaland movement}}\nGorkhaland is the name of the proposed state in India that the [[Nepali language|Nepali]]-speaking [[Indian Gorkha|Gorkha]] ethnic group in [[Darjeeling district|Darjeeling]] [[Kalimpong]] and the [[Dooars]] in north of [[West Bengal]] have expressed a desire to create.A demand for a separate administrative unit in Darjeeling has existed since 1909, when the Hillmen's Association of Darjeeling submitted a memorandum to [[Minto-Morley Reforms]] demanding a separate administrative setup. The term ''Gorkhaland'' was coined by [[Subhash Ghisingh]], leader of [[Gorkha National Liberation Front]], who led a violent agitation for its formation in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darjeelingtimes.com/news/Interviews/Interview-with-subash-ghisingh.html|title=Interview with Subhash Ghisingh|work=Darjeeling Times|date=11 January 2008|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> This movement culminated with the formation of Darjeeling Gorkha Hill Council (DGHC) in 1988. The DGHC did not fulfill its goal of forming a new state, which led to the downfall of Subhash Ghisingh<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/03/11/stories/2008031154731100.htm|title=Subhas Ghising resigns|work=The Hindu|date=11 March 2008|accessdate=16 March 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> and the rise of another party [[Gorkha Janmukti Morcha]] (GJM) headed by [[Bimal Gurung]] in 2007, which launched a second agitation for a Gorkhaland state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.rediff.com/column/2010/jun/03/gjm-leader-bimal-gurung-utterly-self-possessed-and-apparently-ruthless.htm|title=GJM leader Bimal Gurung|work=The Hindu|date=3 June 2010|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Formation of GTA ===\nAfter three years of agitation for a state of Gorkhaland led by GJM, the GJM reached an agreement with the state government to form a semi-autonomous body to administer the Darjeeling hills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/nation/article432036.ece|title=Darjeeling issue solved: Mamata|publisher=Express Buzz|date=8 June 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> A bill for the creation of GTA was passed in the [[West Bengal Legislative Assembly]] on 2 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-03/kolkata/30110031_1_territorial-administration-bill-harka-bahadur-chhetri-gjm|title=GTA Bill passed with 54 amendments|work=The Times of India|date=3 September 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> The GTA aimed to have administrative, executive and financial powers but no legislative powers. A 10-member joint verification committee headed by a retired High Court judge examined the demand to bring the Gorkha-inhabited pockets of the Dooars and the [[Terai]] under the GTA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110730/jsp/frontpage/story_14309540.jsp|title=Ex-judge to head hill committee|work=The Telegraph|date=30 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012|location=Calcutta, India}}</ref>\n\n=== Memorandum of Agreement ===\nThe Memorandum of Agreement<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darjeelingtimes.com/images/stories/news_images/2011/jul11/jul15/finalmos.pdf|title=Full text of GTA MoA|work=Darjeeling Times|date=15 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> for GTA was signed on 18 July 2011 at Pintail Village near [[Siliguri]] in the presence of Union Home Minister [[P. Chidambaram]], West Bengal chief minister [[Mamata Banerjee]] and Gorkha Janmukti Morcha leaders.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.indiangorkhas.in/2011/07/gorkhaland-territorial-administration.html|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305003752/http://www.indiangorkhas.in/2011/07/gorkhaland-territorial-administration.html|url-status = dead|archive-date = 2016-03-05|title = Gorkhaland Territorial Administration (GTA)|work = Indian Gorkhas}}</ref> The agreement was signed by West Bengal Home Secretary G.D. Gautama, Union Home Ministry Joint Secretary K.K. Pathak and GJM general secretary Roshan Giri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.outlookindia.com/item.aspx?728097|title=Gorkhaland Territorial Administration Agreement signed|publisher=Outlook|date=18 July 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719180442/http://news.outlookindia.com/item.aspx?728097|archivedate=19 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Demand for GATA ===\nOn 29 October 2011, the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha and the Akhil Bharatiya Adivasi Vikas Parishad (ABAVP), Dooars Unit signed an 18-point agreement at Mongpoo, after which these organizations jointly proposed a new administrative body called the Gorkhaland and Adivasi Territorial Administration (GATA) in place of the GTA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/delhi/plea-to-rename-gorkha-council_738966.html|title=Plea to rename Gorkha council|publisher=Zee News|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> The ABAVP decided to agree to incorporate 196 mouzas of the Dooars and 199 mouzas of the Terai region into the proposed GATA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thestatesman.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=388679&catid=72|title=GJMM-ABAVP joint deputation on GATA|publisher=The Statesman|date=2 November 2011|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== President's assent and high-power committee report ===\nThe [[President of India]] [[Pratibha Patil]] gave her assent to the GTA Bill of West Bengal on 7 March 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/Chunk-HT-UI-IndiaSectionPage-TopStories/President-gives-her-assent-to-the-GTA-Bill/Article1-822330.aspx|title=President gives her assent to the GTA Bill|work=Hindustan Times|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\nThe West Bengal government issued a gazette notification for the GTA Act on 14 March 2012, signalling preparations for elections for the GTA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-15/kolkata/31196654_1_darjeeling-hills-gorkha-janmukti-morcha-gjm|title=Gorkha territory readies for polls|work=The Times of India|date=15 March 2012|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> In a meeting held on 24 March 2012 between GJM leaders and the West Bengal government, it was decided that the election to the GTA would be held in the end of June or in July 2012.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/WestBengal/High-powered-committee-on-GTA-emerges-as-a-perfect-instrument-to-resolve-impasse/Article1-830368.aspx|title=High-powered committee on GTA emerges as a perfect instrument to resolve impasse|work=Hindustan Times|date=24 March 2012|accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref> The Justice Sen Committee would be requested to submit its report on the inclusion of additional areas of Terai and Dooars in the GTA by early June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=757073|title=GJM climbs down GTA demand, says polls in June\u2013July|publisher=Outlook|date=24 March 2012|accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref> The WB government released a list of 45 constituencies of the GTA on 26 May 2012 to which elections are to be held in July 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Gorkhaland-Territorial-Administration-draft-lists-17-new-constituencies/articleshow/13548203.cms|title=Gorkhaland Territorial Administration draft lists 17 new constituencies|work=The Times of India|date=27 May 2012|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> The high-powered committee headed by retired judge [[Shyamal Kumar Sen]] that was set up by the West Bengal government recommended inclusion of just five [[mouza]]s under the proposed GTA although the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha had demanded 398 mouzas from the Dooars and Terai regions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/darjeeling-might-be-violent-again/articleshow/13966042.cms|title=Darjeeling might be violent again|work=The Economic Times|date=9 June 2012|accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref> The West Bengal government announced that it would set up a three-member \"Fact Verification Committee\" to go into the recommendations of Justice Sen Committee after the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha rejected its report.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/generalnews/news/govt-to-setfact-verification-committeegjm-demand/21365/|title=Govt to set up Fact Verification committee on GJM demand|work=Business Standard|date=16 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> The [[Calcutta High Court]] admitted on 19 June 2012 the case moved by Gorkha National Liberation Front leader Subhash Ghisingh challenging the legality of the GTA. Justice Dipankar Dutta told the three signatories to the GTA agreement \u2013 the central government, the state government and the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha \u2013 to file affidavits stating their stand on Ghisingh's contention.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120620/jsp/siliguri/story_15631990.jsp#.T-H8sbWES8o|title=HC allows Ghisingh GTA plea \u2013 Affidavit order for govts & Morcha|work=The Telegraph|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=20 June 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Our|last=Legal}}</ref>\n\n== GTA election 2012 ==\nThe West Bengal government announced that the election for the GTA would be held on 29 July 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-26/kolkata/32424010_1_gorkha-janmukti-morcha-gjm-shyamal-sen-committee-report|title=State sets July 29 date for GTA polls|work=The Times of India|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> The Gorkha Janmukti Morcha announced that it would contest the GTA polls, which it had earlier threatened to boycott over the Justice Sen-headed committee recommendations on territorial inclusion of the Dooars and Terai that it had rejected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/WestBengal/Gorkha-Janmukti-Morcha-to-contest-GTA-elections/Article1-881430.aspx|title=Gorkha Janmukti Morcha to contest GTA elections|work=The Hindustan Times|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701015423/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/WestBengal/Gorkha-Janmukti-Morcha-to-contest-GTA-elections/Article1-881430.aspx|archivedate=1 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After a period of silence, the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha announced the names of its GTA election nominees.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120706/jsp/siliguri/story_15697611.jsp|title=GTA list of 32 but no Gurung|work=The Telegraph|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Vivek|last=Chhetri}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120707/jsp/frontpage/story_15700400.jsp|title=Gurung in GTA fray|work=The Telegraph|date=6 July 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Vivek|last=Chhetri}}</ref> Parties that formed the Gorkhaland Task Force ([[Communist Party of Revolutionary Marxists|CPRM]], [[ABGL]], [[Bharatiya Gorkha Parisangh]], [[Gorkha National Liberation Front (C.K. Pradhan)|GNLF(C)]], Gorkhaland Rajya Nirman Morcha and others) decided not contest the GTA elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.news.yahoo.com/gjm-faces-heat-rival-parties-strong-arm-tactics-144738644.html|title=GJM faces heat from rival parties for strong-arm tactics|publisher=Yahoo News|date=7 July 2012|accessdate=8 July 2012}}</ref> Both [[CPI(M)]] and [[Trinamool Congress]] fielded candidates in the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/darjeeling-gta-election-is-taking-one-sided-shape/articleshow/14717481.cms|title=Darjeeling GTA election is taking one sided shape|work=The Economic Times|date=6 July 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> The GNLF decided to boycott the elections and its chairman filed a case in the Kolkata High Court challenging the GTA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/article3583517.ece|title=Gurung challenges Ghising to contest GTA polls|work=The Hindu|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012|location=Chennai, India|first=Marcus|last=Dam}}</ref> The CPI(M) withdrew the nominations of all its 13 candidates from the GTA elections, alleging threats and intimidation by the GJM<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstrackindia.com/newsdetails/2012/07/12/254--All-CPI-M-candidates-pull-out-of-Gorkhaland-polls-.html|title=All CPI-M candidates pull out of Gorkhaland polls|publisher=News track India/IANS|date=12 July 2012|accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref> and the GJM received 28 seats of the GTA uncontested.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120713/jsp/siliguri/story_15722547.jsp|title=Morcha gets 28, Gurung thanks CPM|work=The Telegraph|date=13 July 2012|accessdate=15 July 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first1=Vivek|last1=Chhetri|first2=Avijit|last2=Sinha}}</ref> In the elections of the remaining 17 seats of the GTA held on 29 July 2012, GJM candidates won from all the constituencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darjeelingtimes.com/main-news/politics/4936-gjm-sweeps-maiden-gta-polls-not-to-give-up-gorkhaland-demand.html|title=GJM sweeps maiden GTA polls, not to give up Gorkhaland demand|publisher=Darjeeling Times/IANS|date=2 August 2012|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> Sanchabir Subba, the rebel GJM candidate from Gitdabling-Nimbong, narrowly lost to the party's official contestant Kalyan Dewan by 677 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120803/jsp/siliguri/story_15806782.jsp#.UB4clk0gfao|title=Lone rebel Subba loses|work=The Telegraph|date=3 August 2012|accessdate=5 August 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Rajeev|last=Ravidas}}</ref> The newly elected members of the GTA were sworn in on 4 August 2012 at Darjeeling in the presence of home minister [[Sushil Kumar Shinde]] and West Bengal chief minister Mamata Banerjee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Gorkha-Territorial-Administration-members-sworn-in-Shinde-Mamata-assure-support/articleshow/15352094.cms |title=Gorkha Territorial Administration members sworn in; Shinde, Mamata assure support |work=The Times of India |date=5 August 2012 |accessdate=5 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804212156/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Gorkha-Territorial-Administration-members-sworn-in-Shinde-Mamata-assure-support/articleshow/15352094.cms |archivedate=4 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n{{electiontable|Gorkhaland Territorial Administration election, 2012 |Summary of results of the Gorkhaland Territorial Administration election, 2012|sortable=yes}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://darjeeling.gov.in/GTAelected_candidates.html|title=GTA Elections 2012|work=Darjeeling.gov.in|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n|-\n|<!-- color -->\n|Political Party\n|Seats Contested\n|Seats Won\n|Net Change in Seats\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Gorkha Janmukti Morcha}}\n||45||45||-|-\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|All India Trinamool Congress}}\n||17||0||-|-\n|-\n|}\n\n== Regional Political Parties of Gorkhaland ==\n* [[Gorkha Janmukti Morcha]] (GJM)\n* [[Gorkha National Liberation Front]] (GNLF)\n* [[Gorkha National Liberation Front (C.K. Pradhan)]] (GNLF-P)\n* [[Gorkha Rashtriya Congress]]\n* [[Akhil Bharatiya Gorkha League]] / All India Gorkha League (ABGL)\n* [[Bharatiya Gorkha Janashakti]]\n* [[Bharatiya Gorkha Parisangh]] \n* [[Communist Party of Revolutionary Marxists]] (CPRM)\n* [[Sikkim Rashtriya Mukti Morcha]] (SRMM)\n* [[Gorkhaland Rajya Nirman Morcha]] (GRNM)\n* [[Darjeeling Sikkim Merger Forum]] (DSMF)\n* [[Bharatiya Nepali Bir Gorkha]] (BNBG)\n* [[Matri Bhumi Surakhsa Sangathan]] (MBSS)\n* [[Jan Andolan Party]] (JAP)\n* [[Tarai Gorkha Ekta Sangh]] (TGES)\n=== Defunct Political Parties of Gorkhaland ===\n* [[Sikkim Janashakti Party ]] (SJP) {merged with [[Indian National Congress]] in 1999}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Autonomous regions of India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Autonomous administrative divisions of India}}\n\n[[Category:Politics of Gorkhaland]]\n[[Category:Government of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Autonomous regions of India]]\n[[Category:2011 in Indian politics]]\n[[Category:Politics of Darjeeling district]]\n[[Category:Darjeeling district]]\n[[Category:Kalimpong district]]\n", "name_user": "Nidhishach", "label": "safe", "comment": "i have added the former president name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gorkhaland_Territorial_Administration"}
{"title_page": "2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n|tourney_name   = Copa Am\u00e9rica\n|year           = 2021\n|other_titles   = CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica Argentina-Colombia 2021\n|image          = 2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica logo.svg\n|size           = \n|caption        =\n|country        = Argentina\n|country2       = Colombia\n|dates          = 11 June \u2013 11 July 2021\n|num_teams      = 12\n|confederations = 2\n|venues         = 9\n|cities         = 9\n|champion       =\n|count          =\n|second         =\n|third          =\n|fourth         =\n|matches        =\n|goals          =\n|attendance     =\n|top_scorer     =\n|player         =\n|young_player   =\n|goalkeeper     =\n|fair_play      =\n|prevseason     = [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019]]\n|nextseason     = ''[[2024 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2024]]''\n}}\nThe '''2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica''' will be the 47th edition of the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]], the international men's [[association football|football]] championship organized by South America's football ruling body [[CONMEBOL]]. The tournament will take place in [[Colombia]] and [[Argentina]] from 11 June to 11 July 2021. This will mark the first time it will be hosted by more than one country since [[1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1983]], when it was played in a home\u2013away basis, and the first time in two countries.\n\nThe tournament was originally scheduled to take place from 12 June to 12 July 2020. On 17 March 2020, CONMEBOL announced that due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America|coronavirus pandemic]], the tournament had been postponed for a year, in conjunction with [[UEFA]]'s decision to also postpone [[UEFA Euro 2020]] to 2021.<ref name=\"postponed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/comunicado-oficial-2|title=Comunicado Oficial|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] are the title holders, having won their ninth title in [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019]].\n\n==Background==\nIn March 2017, CONMEBOL reportedly proposed that the Copa Am\u00e9rica take place in 2020 as part of a calendar change.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gonzalez |first=Roger |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/the-copa-america-is-reportedlly-coming-back-to-the-united-states-in-2020/ |title=The Copa America is reportedly coming back to the United States in 2020 |website=[[CBSSports.com]] |publisher=CBS Interactive |date=20 March 2017 |access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref> Following the [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019 edition]] in Brazil, the quadrennial tournament would move from odd to even years starting in 2020, with the following edition taking place in Ecuador in [[2024 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2024]]. This would move the tournament in line with the [[UEFA European Championship]], which is also held in even years with a [[UEFA Euro 2020|2020 edition]] taking place.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fernandez |first=Mart\u00edn |url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/noticia/2017/03/copa-america-passa-ser-disputada-junto-com-eurocopa-partir-de-2020.html |title=Conmebol far\u00e1 Copa Am\u00e9rica nos mesmos anos da Euro a partir de 2020 |trans-title=CONMEBOL to have Copa Am\u00e9rica in same years of Euros from 2020 |website=Globo Esporte |publisher=[[Grupo Globo]] |date=20 March 2017 |access-date=26 October 2018 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> Reports suggested that the United States may host the tournament, having previously held the one-off [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario]] in 2016, which celebrated the centenary of CONMEBOL and the Copa Am\u00e9rica.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wahl |first=Grant |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2017/03/24/copa-america-conmebol-concacaf-2020-usa |title=Wheels are in motion for another combined Copa America in USA for 2020 |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher=Meredith Corporation |date=24 March 2017 |access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref> On 18 September 2018, plans for a calendar change were confirmed by CONMEBOL president [[Alejandro Dom\u00ednguez (football executive)|Alejandro Dom\u00ednguez]] after submitting an official request to FIFA.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.supersport.com/football/news/180919_CONMEBOL_to_change_Copa_America_calender |title=CONMEBOL to change Copa America calendar |website=[[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|SuperSport]] |publisher=Naspers |date=18 September 2018 |access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2018 at the [[FIFA Council]] meeting in [[Kigali]], Rwanda, the request was approved for the Copa Am\u00e9rica to take place in even years, starting with the 2020 edition.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gabilondo |first=Aritz |url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/10/26/internacional/1540552736_779766.html |title=Oficial: la Copa Am\u00e9rica ser\u00e1 los a\u00f1os pares desde 2020 |trans-title=Official: Copa Am\u00e9rica will be in even years from 2020 |website=[[Diario AS]] |publisher=PRISA |date=26 October 2018 |access-date=26 October 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref> The tournament will take place between 12 June and 12 July 2020, the same dates as [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref name=\"FIFA\">{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2018/m=10/news=fifa-council-makes-key-decisions-for-the-future-of-football-development.html |title=FIFA Council makes key decisions for the future of football development |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=26 October 2018 |access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2019 CONMEBOL announced [[Argentina]] and [[Colombia]] as co-hosts of the 2020 event after the United States bid was rejected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/consejo-aprueba-realizar-copa-america-2020-en-sudamerica|title=Consejo aprueba realizar Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 en Sudam\u00e9rica|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|date=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mundoalbiceleste.com/2019/03/13/argentina-and-colombia-to-host-2020-copa-america/ |title=Argentina and Colombia to host 2020 Copa America |publisher=Mundo Albiceleste Argentina |date=13 March 2019 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> It was officially announced the same day when CONMEBOL approved of the joint hosting. It was officially awarded on 9 April 2019 at the CONMEBOL Congress in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-copa-america-2020-se-disputara-en-dos-zonas-de-sudamerica-para-acercar-los-partidos-de|title=La Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 en dos zonas de Sudam\u00e9rica para acercar los partidos de selecciones a sus aficionados {{!}} CONMEBOL|website=www.conmebol.com|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Coronavirus pandemic and postponement==\nIn March 2020, the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America|pandemic in South America]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) began [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports#Association football|impacting football]]. FIFA announced that the first two rounds of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|South American qualifiers for the 2022 World Cup]], due to take place in March, were postponed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers-in-south-america |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers in South America |publisher=FIFA.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> while CONMEBOL temporarily suspended the [[2020 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-conmebol-libertadores-queda-suspendida-temporalmente |title=La CONMEBOL Libertadores queda suspendida temporalmente |publisher=CONMEBOL.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March 2020, CONMEBOL announced that the Copa Am\u00e9rica would be postponed to the following year, taking place from 11 June to 11 July 2021, in order to protect the health and safety of the teams, media, visitors and host cities.<ref name=\"postponed\"/> On the following day, the Bureau of the [[FIFA Council]] approved the date change in the [[FIFA International Match Calendar]]. As a result, the [[2021 FIFA Club World Cup|expanded FIFA Club World Cup]], which was due to take place in June and July 2021, will be rescheduled.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/bureau-of-the-fifa-council-decisions-concerning-impact-of-covid-19 |title=Bureau of the FIFA Council decisions concerning impact of COVID-19 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Venues==\nThe tournament will take place in 9 venues in 9 cities, five in [[Argentina]] and four in [[Colombia]]. On 20 November 2019, CONMEBOL published a document confirming 8 venues, [[Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes]] in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[Estadio Malvinas Argentinas]] in [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]], [[Estadio Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]] in [[Buenos Aires]] and [[Estadio Ciudad de La Plata]] in [[La Plata]] for Argentina and [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Pascual Guerrero]] in [[Cali]], [[Atanasio Girardot Sports Complex|Estadio Atanasio Girardot]] in [[Medell\u00edn]], [[Estadio Metropolitano Roberto Mel\u00e9ndez]] in [[Barranquilla]] and [[Estadio El Camp\u00edn]] in [[Bogot\u00e1]] for Colombia. Moreover, [[Estadio San Juan del Bicentenario]] in [[San Juan, Argentina|San Juan]] and [[Estadio Hern\u00e1n Ram\u00edrez Villegas]] in [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]] were also nominated but not confirmed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/sites/default/files/pliego_en_espanol_agencia_digital_dentsu_27112019_nuevasfechas.pdf|title=Pliego de Bases y Condiciones \"Contenido y Gesti\u00f3n de Canales Digitales para CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020\"|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|date=20 November 2019|language=es}}</ref> being finally dismissed.\n\nOn 3 December 2019, prior to the draw, it was known that [[Estadio \u00danico de Santiago del Estero|Estadio \u00danico]] in [[Santiago del Estero]] was included as one of the Argentine venues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iamnoticias.com.ar/2019/12/03/copa-america-cambio-de-estadio/|title=Copa Am\u00e9rica: cambio de estadio|publisher=IAM Noticias|date=3 December 2019|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elliberal.com.ar/noticia/512985/santiago-estero-sera-sede-copa-america-2020|title=Santiago del Estero ser\u00e1 sede de la Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020|publisher=El Liberal|date=3 December 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\nColombia will host the North Zone group, while Argentina will host the South Zone group. Each country will also host two quarter-finals and one semi-final. The third place match and final will be played in Colombia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/argentina-inaugurara-la-conmebol-copa-america-2020-y-colombia-acogera-la-gran-final-diecinueve-anos|title=Argentina inaugurar\u00e1 la CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 y Colombia acoger\u00e1 la gran final|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|date=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!colspan=\"20\"|{{flagicon|ARG}} Argentina\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[Buenos Aires]]\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[La Plata]]\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]]\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[Santiago del Estero]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio Ciudad de La Plata]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio Malvinas Argentinas]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio \u00danico de Santiago del Estero|Estadio \u00danico]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''70,074'''\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''57,000'''\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''53,000'''\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''49,268'''\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''33,000'''<br><small>''(under construction)''</small>\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[File:Superclasico_-_River_Plate_vs_Boca_Juniors_-_Nov._16,_2010_(5196598538).jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[File:Estadio Kempes luego de finalizar un partido.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[File:Estadio Ciudad de La Plata 20140510 2.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[File:Estadio_Malvinas_Argentinas_2012.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"4\"|\n|-\n!colspan=\"8\"|\nArgentina\n{{location map+|float=center|Argentina|width=420|caption=|places=\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-34.913879 |long=-57.988979 |label=[[La Plata]] |position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-31.420100 |long=-64.188800 |label=[[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] |position=left }}\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-34.603333 |long=-58.381667 |label=[[Buenos Aires]] |position=right }}\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-32.883332 |long=-68.816667 |label=[[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]] |position=right }}\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-27.783333 |long=-64.266667 |label=[[Santiago del Estero]] |position=left }}\n}}\n!colspan=\"12\"|\nColombia\n{{location map+|float=center|Colombia|width=630|caption=|places=\n{{location map~ |Colombia |lat=10.963889 |long=-74.796389 |label=[[Barranquilla]] |position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Colombia |lat=6.230833 |long=-75.590556 |label=[[Medell\u00edn]] |position=right }}\n{{location map~ |Colombia |lat=3.420556 |long=-76.522222 |label=[[Cali]] |position=right }}\n{{location map~ |Colombia |lat=4.711111 |long=-74.072222 |label=[[Bogot\u00e1]] |position=right }}\n}}\n|-\n!colspan=20|{{flagicon|COL}} Colombia\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| [[Barranquilla]]\n!colspan=\"5\"| [[Medell\u00edn]]\n!colspan=\"5\"| [[Bogot\u00e1]]\n!colspan=\"5\"| [[Cali]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[Estadio Metropolitano Roberto Mel\u00e9ndez]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[Atanasio Girardot Sports Complex]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[Estadio El Camp\u00edn]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Pascual Guerrero]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\"| Capacity: '''60,000'''\n|colspan=\"5\"| Capacity: '''46,000'''\n|colspan=\"5\"| Capacity: '''40,000'''\n|colspan=\"5\"| Capacity: '''36,000'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[File:Estadio Metropolitano de Baranquilla 2011.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[File:Atanacio girardot antes de la apertura de los juegos flopped.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[File:El camp\u00edn - 13 September 2011.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[File:Pascual Guerrero U-20WC 2011 CMR-NZL.JPG|200px]] \n|}\n</center>\n\n==Teams==\nAll ten CONMEBOL national teams will participate in the competition, divided into two geographical zones for the group stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-copa-america-2020-se-disputara-en-dos-zonas-de-sudamerica-para-acercar-los-partidos-de|title=La Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 en dos zonas de Sudam\u00e9racercar los partidos de selecciones a sus aficionados|website=www.conmebol.com|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, the CONMEBOL Council officially approved the participation of [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] and [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] as the two invited teams, who were the previous two winners of the [[AFC Asian Cup]].<ref name=\"invited\">{{cite news |location=[[S\u00e3o Paulo]] |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/australia-y-qatar-invitadas-la-conmebol-copa-america-2020 |title=Australia y Qatar, invitadas a la CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 |trans-title=Australia and Qatar invited to the CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 |publisher=[[CONMEBOL]] |date=13 June 2019 |access-date=13 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Australia would be making their debut appearance in the Copa Am\u00e9rica, while Qatar would be making their second appearance, having participated in the previous edition.\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n;CONMEBOL North Zone\n*{{fb|BRA}} (title holders)\n*{{fb|COL}} (co-hosts)\n*{{fb|ECU}}\n*{{fb|PER}}\n*{{fb|VEN}}\n{{Col-3}}\n;CONMEBOL South Zone\n*{{fb|ARG}} (co-hosts)\n*{{fb|BOL}}\n*{{fb|CHI}}\n*{{fb|PAR}}\n*{{fb|URU}}\n{{Col-3}}\n;Invited teams\n*{{fb|AUS}}\n*{{fb|QAT}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Draw==\nThe team allocations of the CONMEBOL members, divided into North Zone and South Zone, were announced on 9 April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=La Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 se disputar\u00e1 en dos zonas de Sudam\u00e9rica para acercar los partidos de selecciones a sus aficionados |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-copa-america-2020-se-disputara-en-dos-zonas-de-sudamerica-para-acercar-los-partidos-de |website=www.conmebol.com |accessdate=9 April 2019 |date=9 April 2019}}</ref> The group stage draw was held on 3 December 2019, 19:30 [[Time in Colombia|COT]] ([[UTC\u221205:00|UTC\u22125]]), in [[Cartagena, Colombia|Cartagena]], Colombia to decide the zones of the two invited nations, Australia and Qatar, as well as the schedule of both groups. As hosts, Argentina and Colombia were automatically allocated to positions A1 and B1, respectively.<ref>{{cite tweet |author=[[CONMEBOL]] |user=CopaAmerica |number=1201945186609307648 |date=3 December 2019 |title=Hoy definimos nuestros grupos, seis bolilleros guardan los nombres y las posiciones de nuestras selecciones, no te lo pierdas. (3 de diciembre, 19:30 Colombia) |trans-title=Today we define our groups, six pots keep the names and positions of our national teams, do not miss it. (3 December, 19:30 Colombia) |language=Spanish |access-date=3 December 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203204031/https://twitter.com/CopaAmerica/status/1201945186609307648 |archive-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> The opening match of the tournament will involve Argentina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mundoalbiceleste.com/2019/10/15/argentina-to-start-2020-copa-america-on-june-12-draw-more/|title=Argentina to start 2020 Copa America on June 12, draw, more \u2013 Mundo Albiceleste|last=Nemer|first=Roy|language=en-US|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|\n|- valign=top\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+ [[#Group A (South Zone)|Group A]]<br>(South Zone)\n|-\n! {{Tooltip|Pos|Position}} ||width=120|Team\n|-\n| align=center| A1 || {{fb|ARG}}\n|-\n| align=center| A2 || {{fb|AUS}}\n|-\n| align=center| A3 || {{fb|BOL}}\n|-\n| align=center| A4 || {{fb|URU}}\n|-\n| align=center| A5 || {{fb|CHI}}\n|-\n| align=center| A6 || {{fb|PAR}}\n|}\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+ [[#Group B (North Zone)|Group B]]<br>(North Zone)\n|-\n! {{Tooltip|Pos|Position}} ||width=120|Team\n|-\n| align=center| B1 || {{fb|COL}}\n|-\n| align=center| B2 || {{fb|BRA}}\n|-\n| align=center| B3 || {{fb|QAT}}\n|-\n| align=center| B4 || {{fb|VEN}}\n|-\n| align=center| B5 || {{fb|ECU}}\n|-\n| align=center| B6 || {{fb|PER}}\n|}\n|}\n\nThe fixtures for the group stage were decided based on the draw results, as follows:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcf.com.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/SCHEDULE-CA2020-v8-horarios-004.pdf |title=CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 schedule |website=[[Colombian Football Federation]] |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305010803/https://fcf.com.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/SCHEDULE-CA2020-v8-horarios-004.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Group stage schedule\n|-\n!Matchday\n!Dates\n!Matches\n|-\n|Matchday 1\n|12\u201314 June 2020\n|1 v 5, 2 v 4, 6 v 3\n|-\n|Matchday 2\n|16\u201318 June 2020\n|1 v 4, 6 v 2, 5 v 3\n|-\n|Matchday 3\n|20\u201323 June 2020\n|1 v 6, 2 v 3, 4 v 5\n|-\n|Matchday 4\n|25\u201328 June 2020\n|2 v 1, 3 v 4, 5 v 6\n|-\n|Matchday 5\n|30 June \u2013 1 July 2020\n|3 v 1, 5 v 2, 4 v 6\n|}\n\n==Group stage==\n{{out of date|section|date=March 2020}}\nThe kick-off times for the tournament were announced on 4 March 2020. All match times listed are local, [[Time in Argentina|ART]] ([[UTC\u221203:00|UTC\u22123]]) in Argentina and [[Time in Colombia|COT]] ([[UTC\u221205:00|UTC\u22125]]) in Colombia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fcf.com.co/index.php/2020/03/04/horarios-de-los-partidos-de-la-seleccion-colombia-en-copa-america/ |title=Horarios de los partidos de la Selecci\u00f3n Colombia en Copa Am\u00e9rica |trans-title=Schedule of the Colombia national team's matches at the Copa Am\u00e9rica |work=[[Colombian Football Federation]] |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=5 March 2020 |language=Spanish |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012817/https://fcf.com.co/index.php/2020/03/04/horarios-de-los-partidos-de-la-seleccion-colombia-en-copa-america/ |archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March 2020, the tournament was postponed until 2021 and the new schedule is to be announced.\n\nThe top four teams of each group will advance to the quarter-finals.\n\n===Group A (South Zone)===\n{{Main|2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A}}\n{{2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica group tables|Group A|only_pld_pts=no_hide_class_rules}}\n\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A01}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A02}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A03}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A04}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A05}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A06}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A07}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A08}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A09}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A10}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A11}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A12}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A13}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A14}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A15}}\n\n===Group B (North Zone)===\n{{Main|2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B}}\n{{2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica group tables|Group B|only_pld_pts=no_hide_class_rules}}\n\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B01}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B02}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B03}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B04}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B05}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B06}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B07}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B08}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B09}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B10}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B11}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B12}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B13}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B14}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B15}}\n\n==Knockout stage==\n{{Main|2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage}}\n\n===Bracket===\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|Bracket}}\n\n===Quarter-finals===\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|QF1}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|QF2}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|QF3}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|QF4}}\n\n===Semi-finals===\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|SF1}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|SF2}}\n\n===Third place play-off===\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|TPP}}\n\n===Final===\n<!--{{Main|2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Final}}-->\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica knockout stage|Final}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://copaamerica.com/}}\n*[http://www.conmebol.com/es/copa-america-2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020], CONMEBOL.com\n\n{{2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2020 Copa America}}\n[[Category:2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica| ]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica tournaments]]\n[[Category:Scheduled association football competitions|Copa America 2020]]\n[[Category:2021 in Argentine football]]\n[[Category:2021 in Colombian football]]\n[[Category:2021 in South American football]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by Argentina]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by Colombia]]\n[[Category:June 2021 sports events in South America|Copa America]]\n[[Category:July 2021 sports events in South America|Copa America]]\n[[Category:Sports events postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Copa America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n|tourney_name   = Copa Am\u00e9rica\n|year           = 2021\n|other_titles   = CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica Argentina-Colombia 2021\n|image          = 2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica logo.svg\n|size           = \n|caption        =\n|country        = Argentina\n|country2       = Colombia\n|dates          = 11 June \u2013 11 July 2021\n|num_teams      = 12\n|confederations = 2\n|venues         = 9\n|cities         = 9\n|champion       =\n|count          =\n|second         =\n|third          =\n|fourth         =\n|matches        =\n|goals          =\n|attendance     =\n|top_scorer     =\n|player         =\n|young_player   =\n|goalkeeper     =\n|fair_play      =\n|prevseason     = [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019]]\n|nextseason     = ''[[2024 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2024]]''\n}}\nThe '''2021 Copa Am\u00e9rica''' will be the 47th edition of the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]], the international men's [[association football|football]] championship organized by South America's football ruling body [[CONMEBOL]]. The tournament will take place in [[Colombia]] and [[Argentina]] from 11 June to 11 July 2021. This will mark the first time it will be hosted by more than one country since [[1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1983]], when it was played in a home\u2013away basis, and the first time in two countries.\n\nThe tournament was originally scheduled to take place from 12 June to 12 July 2020. On 17 March 2020, CONMEBOL announced that due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America|coronavirus pandemic]], the tournament had been postponed for a year, in conjunction with [[UEFA]]'s decision to also postpone [[UEFA Euro 2020]] to 2021.<ref name=\"postponed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/comunicado-oficial-2|title=Comunicado Oficial|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] are the title holders, having won their ninth title in [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019]].\n\n==Background==\nIn March 2017, CONMEBOL reportedly proposed that the Copa Am\u00e9rica take place in 2020 as part of a calendar change.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gonzalez |first=Roger |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/the-copa-america-is-reportedlly-coming-back-to-the-united-states-in-2020/ |title=The Copa America is reportedly coming back to the United States in 2020 |website=[[CBSSports.com]] |publisher=CBS Interactive |date=20 March 2017 |access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref> Following the [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019 edition]] in Brazil, the quadrennial tournament would move from odd to even years starting in 2020, with the following edition taking place in Ecuador in [[2024 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2024]]. This would move the tournament in line with the [[UEFA European Championship]], which is also held in even years with a [[UEFA Euro 2020|2020 edition]] taking place.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fernandez |first=Mart\u00edn |url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/noticia/2017/03/copa-america-passa-ser-disputada-junto-com-eurocopa-partir-de-2020.html |title=Conmebol far\u00e1 Copa Am\u00e9rica nos mesmos anos da Euro a partir de 2020 |trans-title=CONMEBOL to have Copa Am\u00e9rica in same years of Euros from 2020 |website=Globo Esporte |publisher=[[Grupo Globo]] |date=20 March 2017 |access-date=26 October 2018 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> Reports suggested that the United States may host the tournament, having previously held the one-off [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario]] in 2016, which celebrated the centenary of CONMEBOL and the Copa Am\u00e9rica.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wahl |first=Grant |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2017/03/24/copa-america-conmebol-concacaf-2020-usa |title=Wheels are in motion for another combined Copa America in USA for 2020 |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher=Meredith Corporation |date=24 March 2017 |access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref> On 18 September 2018, plans for a calendar change were confirmed by CONMEBOL president [[Alejandro Dom\u00ednguez (football executive)|Alejandro Dom\u00ednguez]] after submitting an official request to FIFA.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.supersport.com/football/news/180919_CONMEBOL_to_change_Copa_America_calender |title=CONMEBOL to change Copa America calendar |website=[[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|SuperSport]] |publisher=Naspers |date=18 September 2018 |access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2018 at the [[FIFA Council]] meeting in [[Kigali]], Rwanda, the request was approved for the Copa Am\u00e9rica to take place in even years, starting with the 2020 edition.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gabilondo |first=Aritz |url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/10/26/internacional/1540552736_779766.html |title=Oficial: la Copa Am\u00e9rica ser\u00e1 los a\u00f1os pares desde 2020 |trans-title=Official: Copa Am\u00e9rica will be in even years from 2020 |website=[[Diario AS]] |publisher=PRISA |date=26 October 2018 |access-date=26 October 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref> The tournament will take place between 12 June and 12 July 2020, the same dates as [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref name=\"FIFA\">{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2018/m=10/news=fifa-council-makes-key-decisions-for-the-future-of-football-development.html |title=FIFA Council makes key decisions for the future of football development |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=26 October 2018 |access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2019 CONMEBOL announced [[Argentina]] and [[Colombia]] as co-hosts of the 2020 event after the United States bid was rejected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/consejo-aprueba-realizar-copa-america-2020-en-sudamerica|title=Consejo aprueba realizar Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 en Sudam\u00e9rica|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|date=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mundoalbiceleste.com/2019/03/13/argentina-and-colombia-to-host-2020-copa-america/ |title=Argentina and Colombia to host 2020 Copa America |publisher=Mundo Albiceleste Argentina |date=13 March 2019 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> It was officially announced the same day when CONMEBOL approved of the joint hosting. It was officially awarded on 9 April 2019 at the CONMEBOL Congress in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-copa-america-2020-se-disputara-en-dos-zonas-de-sudamerica-para-acercar-los-partidos-de|title=La Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 en dos zonas de Sudam\u00e9rica para acercar los partidos de selecciones a sus aficionados {{!}} CONMEBOL|website=www.conmebol.com|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Coronavirus pandemic and postponement==\nIn March 2020, the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America|pandemic in South America]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) began [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports#Association football|impacting football]]. FIFA announced that the first two rounds of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|South American qualifiers for the 2022 World Cup]], due to take place in March, were postponed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers-in-south-america |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers in South America |publisher=FIFA.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> while CONMEBOL temporarily suspended the [[2020 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-conmebol-libertadores-queda-suspendida-temporalmente |title=La CONMEBOL Libertadores queda suspendida temporalmente |publisher=CONMEBOL.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March 2020, CONMEBOL announced that the Copa Am\u00e9rica would be postponed to the following year, taking place from 11 June to 11 July 2021, in order to protect the health and safety of the teams, media, visitors and host cities.<ref name=\"postponed\"/> On the following day, the Bureau of the [[FIFA Council]] approved the date change in the [[FIFA International Match Calendar]]. As a result, the [[2021 FIFA Club World Cup|expanded FIFA Club World Cup]], which was due to take place in June and July 2021, will be rescheduled.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/bureau-of-the-fifa-council-decisions-concerning-impact-of-covid-19 |title=Bureau of the FIFA Council decisions concerning impact of COVID-19 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Venues==\nThe tournament will take place in 9 venues in 9 cities, five in [[Argentina]] and four in [[Colombia]]. On 20 November 2019, CONMEBOL published a document confirming 8 venues, [[Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes]] in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[Estadio Malvinas Argentinas]] in [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]], [[Estadio Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]] in [[Buenos Aires]] and [[Estadio Ciudad de La Plata]] in [[La Plata]] for Argentina and [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Pascual Guerrero]] in [[Cali]], [[Atanasio Girardot Sports Complex|Estadio Atanasio Girardot]] in [[Medell\u00edn]], [[Estadio Metropolitano Roberto Mel\u00e9ndez]] in [[Barranquilla]] and [[Estadio El Camp\u00edn]] in [[Bogot\u00e1]] for Colombia. Moreover, [[Estadio San Juan del Bicentenario]] in [[San Juan, Argentina|San Juan]] and [[Estadio Hern\u00e1n Ram\u00edrez Villegas]] in [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]] were also nominated but not confirmed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/sites/default/files/pliego_en_espanol_agencia_digital_dentsu_27112019_nuevasfechas.pdf|title=Pliego de Bases y Condiciones \"Contenido y Gesti\u00f3n de Canales Digitales para CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020\"|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|date=20 November 2019|language=es}}</ref> being finally dismissed.\n\nOn 3 December 2019, prior to the draw, it was known that [[Estadio \u00danico de Santiago del Estero|Estadio \u00danico]] in [[Santiago del Estero]] was included as one of the Argentine venues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iamnoticias.com.ar/2019/12/03/copa-america-cambio-de-estadio/|title=Copa Am\u00e9rica: cambio de estadio|publisher=IAM Noticias|date=3 December 2019|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elliberal.com.ar/noticia/512985/santiago-estero-sera-sede-copa-america-2020|title=Santiago del Estero ser\u00e1 sede de la Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020|publisher=El Liberal|date=3 December 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\nColombia will host the North Zone group, while Argentina will host the South Zone group. Each country will also host two quarter-finals and one semi-final. The third place match and final will be played in Colombia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/argentina-inaugurara-la-conmebol-copa-america-2020-y-colombia-acogera-la-gran-final-diecinueve-anos|title=Argentina inaugurar\u00e1 la CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 y Colombia acoger\u00e1 la gran final|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|date=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!colspan=\"20\"|{{flagicon|ARG}} Argentina\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[Buenos Aires]]\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[La Plata]]\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]]\n!colspan=\"4\"| [[Santiago del Estero]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio Antonio Vespucio Liberti|Estadio Monumental]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio Ciudad de La Plata]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio Malvinas Argentinas]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[Estadio \u00danico de Santiago del Estero|Estadio \u00danico]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''70,074'''\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''57,000'''\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''53,000'''\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''49,268'''\n|colspan=\"4\"| Capacity: '''33,000'''<br><small>''(under construction)''</small>\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[File:Superclasico_-_River_Plate_vs_Boca_Juniors_-_Nov._16,_2010_(5196598538).jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[File:Estadio Kempes luego de finalizar un partido.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[File:Estadio Ciudad de La Plata 20140510 2.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"4\"| [[File:Estadio_Malvinas_Argentinas_2012.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"4\"|\n|-\n!colspan=\"8\"|\nArgentina\n{{location map+|float=center|Argentina|width=420|caption=|places=\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-34.913879 |long=-57.988979 |label=[[La Plata]] |position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-31.420100 |long=-64.188800 |label=[[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] |position=left }}\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-34.603333 |long=-58.381667 |label=[[Buenos Aires]] |position=right }}\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-32.883332 |long=-68.816667 |label=[[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]] |position=right }}\n{{location map~ |Argentina |lat=-27.783333 |long=-64.266667 |label=[[Santiago del Estero]] |position=left }}\n}}\n!colspan=\"12\"|\nColombia\n{{location map+|float=center|Colombia|width=630|caption=|places=\n{{location map~ |Colombia |lat=10.963889 |long=-74.796389 |label=[[Barranquilla]] |position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Colombia |lat=6.230833 |long=-75.590556 |label=[[Medell\u00edn]] |position=right }}\n{{location map~ |Colombia |lat=3.420556 |long=-76.522222 |label=[[Cali]] |position=right }}\n{{location map~ |Colombia |lat=4.711111 |long=-74.072222 |label=[[Bogot\u00e1]] |position=right }}\n}}\n|-\n!colspan=20|{{flagicon|COL}} Colombia\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| [[Barranquilla]]\n!colspan=\"5\"| [[Medell\u00edn]]\n!colspan=\"5\"| [[Bogot\u00e1]]\n!colspan=\"5\"| [[Cali]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[Estadio Metropolitano Roberto Mel\u00e9ndez]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[Atanasio Girardot Sports Complex]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[Estadio El Camp\u00edn]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Pascual Guerrero]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\"| Capacity: '''60,000'''\n|colspan=\"5\"| Capacity: '''46,000'''\n|colspan=\"5\"| Capacity: '''40,000'''\n|colspan=\"5\"| Capacity: '''36,000'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[File:Estadio Metropolitano de Baranquilla 2011.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[File:Atanacio girardot antes de la apertura de los juegos flopped.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[File:El camp\u00edn - 13 September 2011.jpg|200px]]\n|colspan=\"5\"| [[File:Pascual Guerrero U-20WC 2011 CMR-NZL.JPG|200px]] \n|}\n</center>\n\n==Teams==\nAll ten CONMEBOL national teams will participate in the competition, divided into two geographical zones for the group stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-copa-america-2020-se-disputara-en-dos-zonas-de-sudamerica-para-acercar-los-partidos-de|title=La Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 en dos zonas de Sudam\u00e9racercar los partidos de selecciones a sus aficionados|website=www.conmebol.com|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, the CONMEBOL Council officially approved the participation of [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] and [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] as the two invited teams, who were the previous two winners of the [[AFC Asian Cup]].<ref name=\"invited\">{{cite news |location=[[S\u00e3o Paulo]] |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/australia-y-qatar-invitadas-la-conmebol-copa-america-2020 |title=Australia y Qatar, invitadas a la CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 |trans-title=Australia and Qatar invited to the CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 |publisher=[[CONMEBOL]] |date=13 June 2019 |access-date=13 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Australia would be making their debut appearance in the Copa Am\u00e9rica, while Qatar would be making their second appearance, having participated in the previous edition.\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n;CONMEBOL North Zone\n*{{fb|BRA}} (title holders)\n*{{fb|COL}} (co-hosts)\n*{{fb|ECU}}\n*{{fb|PER}}\n*{{fb|VEN}}\n{{Col-3}}\n;CONMEBOL South Zone\n*{{fb|ARG}} (co-hosts)\n*{{fb|BOL}}\n*{{fb|CHI}}\n*{{fb|PAR}}\n*{{fb|URU}}\n{{Col-3}}\n;Invited teams\n*{{fb|AUS}}\n*{{fb|QAT}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Draw==\nThe team allocations of the CONMEBOL members, divided into North Zone and South Zone, were announced on 9 April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=La Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 se disputar\u00e1 en dos zonas de Sudam\u00e9rica para acercar los partidos de selecciones a sus aficionados |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-copa-america-2020-se-disputara-en-dos-zonas-de-sudamerica-para-acercar-los-partidos-de |website=www.conmebol.com |accessdate=9 April 2019 |date=9 April 2019}}</ref> The group stage draw was held on 3 December 2019, 19:30 [[Time in Colombia|COT]] ([[UTC\u221205:00|UTC\u22125]]), in [[Cartagena, Colombia|Cartagena]], Colombia to decide the zones of the two invited nations, Australia and Qatar, as well as the schedule of both groups. As hosts, Argentina and Colombia were automatically allocated to positions A1 and B1, respectively.<ref>{{cite tweet |author=[[CONMEBOL]] |user=CopaAmerica |number=1201945186609307648 |date=3 December 2019 |title=Hoy definimos nuestros grupos, seis bolilleros guardan los nombres y las posiciones de nuestras selecciones, no te lo pierdas. (3 de diciembre, 19:30 Colombia) |trans-title=Today we define our groups, six pots keep the names and positions of our national teams, do not miss it. (3 December, 19:30 Colombia) |language=Spanish |access-date=3 December 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203204031/https://twitter.com/CopaAmerica/status/1201945186609307648 |archive-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> The opening match of the tournament will involve Argentina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mundoalbiceleste.com/2019/10/15/argentina-to-start-2020-copa-america-on-june-12-draw-more/|title=Argentina to start 2020 Copa America on June 12, draw, more \u2013 Mundo Albiceleste|last=Nemer|first=Roy|language=en-US|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|\n|- valign=top\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+ [[#Group A (South Zone)|Group A]]<br>(South Zone)\n|-\n! {{Tooltip|Pos|Position}} ||width=120|Team\n|-\n| align=center| A1 || {{fb|ARG}}\n|-\n| align=center| A2 || {{fb|AUS}}\n|-\n| align=center| A3 || {{fb|BOL}}\n|-\n| align=center| A4 || {{fb|URU}}\n|-\n| align=center| A5 || {{fb|CHI}}\n|-\n| align=center| A6 || {{fb|PAR}}\n|}\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+ [[#Group B (North Zone)|Group B]]<br>(North Zone)\n|-\n! {{Tooltip|Pos|Position}} ||width=120|Team\n|-\n| align=center| B1 || {{fb|COL}}\n|-\n| align=center| B2 || {{fb|BRA}}\n|-\n| align=center| B3 || {{fb|QAT}}\n|-\n| align=center| B4 || {{fb|VEN}}\n|-\n| align=center| B5 || {{fb|ECU}}\n|-\n| align=center| B6 || {{fb|PER}}\n|}\n|}\n\nThe fixtures for the group stage were decided based on the draw results, as follows:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcf.com.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/SCHEDULE-CA2020-v8-horarios-004.pdf |title=CONMEBOL Copa Am\u00e9rica 2020 schedule |website=[[Colombian Football Federation]] |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305010803/https://fcf.com.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/SCHEDULE-CA2020-v8-horarios-004.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Group stage schedule\n|-\n!Matchday\n!Dates\n!Matches\n|-\n|Matchday 1\n|12\u201314 June 2020\n|1 v 5, 2 v 4, 6 v 3\n|-\n|Matchday 2\n|16\u201318 June 2020\n|1 v 4, 6 v 2, 5 v 3\n|-\n|Matchday 3\n|20\u201323 June 2020\n|1 v 6, 2 v 3, 4 v 5\n|-\n|Matchday 4\n|25\u201328 June 2020\n|2 v 1, 3 v 4, 5 v 6\n|-\n|Matchday 5\n|30 June \u2013 1 July 2020\n|3 v 1, 5 v 2, 4 v 6\n|}\n\n==Group stage==\n{{out of date|section|date=March 2020}}\nThe kick-off times for the tournament were announced on 4 March 2020. All match times listed are local, [[Time in Argentina|ART]] ([[UTC\u221203:00|UTC\u22123]]) in Argentina and [[Time in Colombia|COT]] ([[UTC\u221205:00|UTC\u22125]]) in Colombia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fcf.com.co/index.php/2020/03/04/horarios-de-los-partidos-de-la-seleccion-colombia-en-copa-america/ |title=Horarios de los partidos de la Selecci\u00f3n Colombia en Copa Am\u00e9rica |trans-title=Schedule of the Colombia national team's matches at the Copa Am\u00e9rica |work=[[Colombian Football Federation]] |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=5 March 2020 |language=Spanish |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012817/https://fcf.com.co/index.php/2020/03/04/horarios-de-los-partidos-de-la-seleccion-colombia-en-copa-america/ |archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March 2020, the tournament was postponed until 2021 and the new schedule is to be announced.\n\nThe top four teams of each group will advance to the quarter-finals.\n\n===Group A (South Zone)===\n{{Main|2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A}}\n{{2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica group tables|Group A|only_pld_pts=no_hide_class_rules}}\n\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A01}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A02}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A03}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A04}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A05}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A06}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A07}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A08}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A09}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A10}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A11}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A12}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A13}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A14}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group A|A15}}\n\n===Group B (North Zone)===\n{{Main|2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B}}\n{{2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica group tables|Group B|only_pld_pts=no_hide_class_rules}}\n\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B01}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B02}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B03}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B04}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B05}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B06}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B07}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B08}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B09}}\n----\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B10}}\n{{#lst:2020 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|B11}}\n{{